IIRC, there is a jQuery global object available.. you can assign it to a local variable inside in iife, which is the appropriate way to use jQuery when writing a module...<p><pre><code>    (function(window,$){
      //module code goes here
    }(this.self || this, jQuery));
</code></pre>
In this way, you are keeping jQuery itself and your implicit scope assigned to localized variables.<p>If you are writing a modern module (not necessarily jQuery based), then following node/cjs conventions is probably best.  If you use this convention with such a plugin, said module should probably return the jQuery object that has been modified, and extra care should be taken that all plugins are using compatible/same instance of jQuery.
